margin 0.5566 with sanity checks passed; early/middle/late fixed-config LLC zarr traces preserved; no 8M launched.\"\nstate/experiment_registry.csv:8:final_training_20260620T053855Z,02_final_training,passed,structured_pt_seed_a__shuffled_pt__matched_en__structured_pt_seed_b,roneneldan/TinyStories-8M,20260620,98913e931d2dd1ea4453a519b2ff860008cffb69,results/02_final_training/final_training_20260620T053855Z/frozen_config.json,2026-06-20T05:40:01.203847Z,2026-06-20T05:48:36.823238Z,0.1425,0.1425,results/02_final_training/final_training_20260620T053855Z,Final behavior trajectories complete; checkpoint hashes and every-checkpoint BPB/grammar metrics recorded; LLC selection frozen without LLC inspection.\ndocs/04_BENCHMARKS_AND_FERMI_ESTIMATES.md:19:## Benchmark B: sampler\ndocs/04_BENCHMARKS_AND_FERMI_ESTIMATES.md:24:2. run two chains;\ndocs/04_BENCHMARKS_AND_FERMI_ESTIMATES.md:27:5. record wall time, approximate chain-step count, peak VRAM, and output size;\ndocs/04_BENCHMARKS_AND_FERMI_ESTIMATES.md:30:The included `scripts/benchmark_sampler.py` is an API/performance smoke test, not a scientifically valid LLC estimate when used with random tokens.\ndocs/04_BENCHMARKS_AND_FERMI_ESTIMATES.md:46:Illustrative sampler allocation:\ndocs/04_BENCHMARKS_AND_FERMI_ESTIMATES.md:48:| Component | Approx. chain steps |\ndocs/04_BENCHMARKS_AND_FERMI_ESTIMATES.md:55:| transition-region extra chains | 4,000 |\ndocs/04_BENCHMARKS_AND_FERMI_ESTIMATES.md:61:Let `t_train` and `t_sampler` be measured seconds per ordinary and per chain step. A planning estimate is:\ndocs/04_BENCHMARKS_AND_FERMI_ESTIMATES.md:66:\\frac{N_{\\text{sampler}}t_{\\text{sampler}}}{3600}\ndocs/04_BENCHMARKS_AND_FERMI_ESTIMATES.md:75:  --sampler-benchmark results/00_infrastructure_gate/sampler_smoke.json \\\ndocs/04_BENCHMARKS_AND_FERMI_ESTIMATES.md:87:sampler chain step:     0.15–0.80 s\ndocs/04_BENCHMARKS_AND_FERMI_ESTIMATES.md:93:- raw sampler stepping: 1.3–7.0 GPU-hours;\ndocs/04_BENCHMARKS_AND_FERMI_ESTIMATES.md:104:At 7 hours, raw planned compute is about $7. Real project cost is higher because of driver/bootstrap time, sampler failures, idle time, disk, and contingency. Budget:\ndocs/04_BENCHMARKS_AND_FERMI_ESTIMATES.md:118:- reduce LLC checkpoint density;\ndocs/04_BENCHMARKS_AND_FERMI_ESTIMATES.md:119:- retain both controls and diagnostic chains;\ndocs/04_BENCHMARKS_AND_FERMI_ESTIMATES.md:123:- do not use fewer than two chains for a reported estimate.\nscripts/estimate_project.py:15:    p.add_argument(\"--sampler-benchmark\", type=Path, required=True)\nscripts/estimate_project.py:17:    p.add_argument(\"--sampler-chain-steps\", type=int, default=31700)\nscripts/estimate_project.py:28:    sampler = load(args.sampler_benchmark)\nscripts/estimate_project.py:30:    t_sampler = float(sampler[\"seconds_per_chain_step_estimate\"])\nscripts/estimate_project.py:31:    raw_hours = (args.training_steps * t_train + args.sampler_chain_steps * t_sampler) / 3600\nscripts/estimate_project.py:38:            \"sampler_chain_steps\": args.sampler_chain_steps,\nscripts/estimate_project.py:40:            \"seconds_per_sampler_chain_step\": t_sampler,\nscripts/estimate_project.py:60:- Sampler chain step: {t_sampler:.4f} s\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:13:where the checkpoint is the center, the empirical loss and reference dataset define the measured geometry, `n_beta` controls effective inverse temperature, and localization controls how far the sampler can move.\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:17:## Why calling `llc()` is not enough\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:21:The clean theoretical object is associated with local geometry near minima of a population loss. A checkpoint halfway through Portuguese adaptation can have an obvious downhill direction on Portuguese loss. A localized chain can therefore drift toward a better point rather than equilibrate around the checkpoint.\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:23:Inspect whether sampled loss rises from the baseline, reaches a stable range, and remains localized. Persistent loss below the center or monotonic downhill movement is a rejection signal. Increasing localization or adjusting effective temperature may help, but a checkpoint that never admits a stable common protocol should not produce a headline LLC number.\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:27:LLC is not a context-free scalar attached to weights. The sampling dataset, loss, normalization, temperature, localization, and parameterization matter. Use fixed reference sets and compare trajectories within condition. Normalize raw LLC within run for visualization if necessary, but retain raw estimates and settings.\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:31:The three primary knobs are sampler learning rate, `n_beta`, and localization. Burn-in, draw spacing, chain count, draw count, batch size, and preconditioner also matter. A configuration that looks good at one checkpoint may fail elsewhere.\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:45:Use short one-chain traces only to eliminate explosions, zero signal, and obvious drift. These are starting scales from current Timaeus guidance, not universally correct values.\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:49:Take the two or three most plausible configurations and test each at early, middle, and late checkpoints using two chains and longer traces.\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:54:- chain losses plateau after burn-in;\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:57:- chains broadly agree;\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:58:- parameter displacement remains local;\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:66:num_chains            = 3\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:72:This is about 400 chain steps per chain under one common interpretation. Increase chains or draws near the headline interval if between-chain dispersion is high. Do not reduce to one chain to save the project.\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:76:SGLD samples are autocorrelated. Thinning is not a substitute for diagnosis. Plot autocorrelation or estimate an effective sample size, inspect running means, and compare independent chains. A narrow standard error calculated from highly correlated draws is misleading.\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:80:- within-chain Monte Carlo uncertainty;\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:81:- between-chain uncertainty;\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:85:- sampler-hyperparameter sensitivity.\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:91:If training uses weight decay but the sampling loss omits it, or training uses one reduction and the sampler another, the local object changes. For the cleanest first run, use zero weight decay and match next-token cross-entropy exactly. Record whether padding tokens and sequence boundaries are masked identically.\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:95:SLT quantities can depend on parameterization in finite empirical settings. Adapter-only training constrains the path to a low-dimensional subspace. An adapter-only LLC then characterizes that adapter parameterization; a full-model LLC around a mostly frozen network answers another question. Use full-parameter training for the primary study.\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:103:A training-trajectory changepoint in an estimated LLC is not automatically a formal Bayesian phase transition. Use cautious terms:\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:105:- acceptable: “LLC changepoint,” “local geometric reorganization,” “SLT-derived diagnostic”;\ndocs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md:112:A sampler step is roughly a training-like gradient step, but the campaign multiplies steps by chains, checkpoints, and tuning configurations. A plausible campaign contains about 31,700 chain steps versus about 10,000 ordinary training/pilot steps. SGLD is therefore likely to dominate cost even though the model is tiny.\nscripts/benchmark_sampler.py:44:    parser.add_argument(\"--num-chains\", type=int, default=2)\nscripts/benchmark_sampler.py:54:    from devinterp.slt.llc import llc\nscripts/benchmark_sampler.py:58:        raise RuntimeError(\"CUDA is required for the intended cloud sampler benchmark\")\nscripts/benchmark_sampler.py:66:    trace_output = args.output.with_suffix(\".zarr\")\nscripts/benchmark_sampler.py:77:        \"num_chains\": args.num_chains,\nscripts/benchmark_sampler.py:84:    sig = inspect.signature(llc)\nscripts/benchmark_sampler.py:94:    result = llc(**kwargs)\nscripts/benchmark_sampler.py:97:    approx_steps = args.num_chains * (\nscripts/benchmark_sampler.py:101:        \"benchmark\": \"sampler_smoke\",\nscripts/benchmark_sampler.py:107:        \"devinterp_llc_signature\": str(sig),\nscripts/benchmark_sampler.py:108:        \"sampler_config\": {\nscripts/benchmark_sampler.py:121:        \"approx_chain_steps\": approx_steps,\nscripts/benchmark_sampler.py:122:        \"seconds_per_chain_step_estimate\": wall / max(1, approx_steps),\ndocs/00_EXECUTIVE_PLAN.md:7:The model is trained conventionally with AdamW. At selected checkpoints, training stops conceptually: the checkpoint is frozen as a center point, and a separate localized Bayesian sampler probes the nearby loss geometry. This means the training loop itself does not need to become Bayesian, but the entire checkpoint, reference-data, sampler-tuning, diagnostics, and analysis protocol must be designed before the final run.\ndocs/00_EXECUTIVE_PLAN.md:21:- Full LLC trajectory for the first Portuguese seed, reduced LLC replication for the second seed and controls.\ndocs/00_EXECUTIVE_PLAN.md:22:- Complete chain-level sampler diagnostics.\ndocs/00_EXECUTIVE_PLAN.md:31:Intermediate Portuguese checkpoints may not behave like local minima of the Portuguese empirical loss. A localized SGLD chain can drift downhill rather than equilibrate around the checkpoint. If no common localization/temperature configuration yields stable traces across early, middle, and late checkpoints, the intended LLC comparison is not valid. This is a go/no-go gate, not a plot-cleaning problem.\ndocs/00_EXECUTIVE_PLAN.md:39:| Sampler tuning and final LLC campaign | 5 GPU-hours | 2.5–11 |\ndocs/00_EXECUTIVE_PLAN.md:57:2. **Scientific pilot:** structured Portuguese improves, grammar probes pass sanity checks, shuffled control behaves differently, and one common sampler configuration works at three checkpoints.\ndocs/00_EXECUTIVE_PLAN.md:58:3. **Final campaign:** only after the first two gates, run the 8M trajectories and reportable LLC estimates.\ndocs/00_EXECUTIVE_PLAN.md:66:It does not prove a universal language-learning phase transition, a formal Bayesian phase transition, or that LLC caused the capability.\nscripts/validate_handoff.py:13:    \"scripts/benchmark_train.py\", \"scripts/benchmark_sampler.py\",\ndocs/07_ADAPTION_AUTOSCIENTIST_ASSESSMENT.md:65:- selecting sampler settings;\ndocs/07_ADAPTION_AUTOSCIENTIST_ASSESSMENT.md:67:- replacing custom SGLD/LLC execution.\nscripts/scientific_pilot.py:63:    sampler_size: int\nscripts/scientific_pilot.py:68:    sampler_num_chains: int\nscripts/scientific_pilot.py:69:    sampler_burnin: int\nscripts/scientific_pilot.py:70:    sampler_draws: int\nscripts/scientific_pilot.py:71:    sampler_steps_between_draws: int\nscripts/scientific_pilot.py:72:    sampler_lr: float\nscripts/scientific_pilot.py:73:    sampler_n_beta: float\nscripts/scientific_pilot.py:74:    sampler_localization: float\nscripts/scientific_pilot.py:96:            \"sampler_size\": self.sampler_size,\nscripts/scientific_pilot.py:103:            \"sampler\": {\nscripts/scientific_pilot.py:104:                \"num_chains\": self.sampler_num_chains,\nscripts/scientific_pilot.py:105:                \"num_burnin_steps\": self.sampler_burnin,\nscripts/scientific_pilot.py:106:                \"num_draws\": self.sampler_draws,\nscripts/scientific_pilot.py:107:                \"num_steps_between_draws\": self.sampler_steps_between_draws,\nscripts/scientific_pilot.py:108:                \"lr\": self.sampler_lr,\nscripts/scientif